**Prime Number Checker Function**
=====================================

### Function Description

This function takes an array of 5 numbers as input and checks if any of the numbers is a valid prime number. If a prime number is found, it is printed to the console.

### Code

```javascript
/**
 * Checks if any number in the input array is a prime number.
 * 
 * @param {number[]} numbers - An array of 5 numbers.
 */
function checkPrimeNumbers(numbers) {
    // Check if input array has exactly 5 numbers
    if (numbers.length !== 5) {
        throw new Error('Input array must have exactly 5 numbers');
    }

    // Iterate over each number in the array
    numbers.forEach((number) => {
        // Check if number is a prime number
        if (isPrime(number)) {
            // Print prime number to console
            console.log(`Found prime number: ${number}`);
        }
    });
}

/**
 * Checks if a number is a prime number.
 * 
 * @param {number} number - The number to check.
 * @returns {boolean} True if the number is prime, false otherwise.
 */
function isPrime(number) {
    // Check if number is less than 2 (not prime)
    if (number < 2) {
        return false;
    }

    // Check if number is 2 (only even prime number)
    if (number === 2) {
        return true;
    }

    // Check if number is even (not prime)
    if (number % 2 === 0) {
        return false;
    }

    // Check odd factors up to square root of number
    for (let i = 3; i * i <= number; i += 2) {
        if (number % i === 0) {
            return false;
        }
    }

    // If no factors found, number is prime
    return true;
}
```

### Example Use Case

```javascript
// Create an array of 5 numbers
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

// Call the checkPrimeNumbers function
checkPrimeNumbers(numbers);
```

This will output:

```
Found prime number: 2
Found prime number: 3
Found prime number: 5
```

Note that the `isPrime` function uses a simple trial division method to check if a number is prime. This method is sufficient for small numbers, but may not be efficient for larger numbers. For larger numbers, a more advanced primality test such as the Miller-Rabin test may be necessary.

